00:50:32,943 --> 00:50:36,743
Well, your school records have
certainly improved. Mrs. Thurston?

716
00:50:36,914 --> 00:50:37,938
Yes, Your Honor?

717
00:50:38,115 --> 00:50:41,448
You're a counselor at Gracie's school.
What's your assessment?

718
00:50:41,618 --> 00:50:47,557
Gracie is doing extremely well, and l'm
also encouraging her to apply for college.

719
00:50:47,725 --> 00:50:49,886
All of the children are making an effort.

720
00:50:50,527 --> 00:50:54,725
Ryan and Robbie are in special day classes,
and Jonny's pulling in A's.

721
00:50:54,898 --> 00:50:57,162
What happens to them
when Gracie's at work?

722
00:50:57,334 --> 00:51:00,201
My grandmother can come
to my apartment after school...

723
00:51:00,371 --> 00:51:02,464
...or there's foster-family daycare.

724
00:51:02,639 --> 00:51:05,608
l know it's not perfect,
but it's very important to me...

725
00:51:05,776 --> 00:51:08,142
...and to my brothers
that we stay together.

726
00:51:11,281 --> 00:51:15,547
Where is the mother, Rowena Larson?

727
00:51:15,719 --> 00:51:18,916
l talked to her yesterday.
She said she would be here.

728
00:51:20,357 --> 00:51:22,757
Well, how did these children
get here today?

729
00:51:22,926 --> 00:51:25,918
-Easy. We took the bus.
-You don't have a car?

730
00:51:26,096 --> 00:51:28,155
We're getting one.

731
00:51:30,834 --> 00:51:34,429
Look, l don't understand this money
problem with your grandmother.

732
00:51:34,605 --> 00:51:38,063
She's getting $520 a month
for each child.

733
00:51:38,242 --> 00:51:41,905
The thing is, Your Honor, my grandmother
gives the money to my mother.

734
00:51:42,079 --> 00:51:43,569
We don't ever see it.

735
00:51:43,747 --> 00:51:47,979
Gracie buys us our shoes and stuff, sir.
l mean, Your Honor.

736
00:51:48,152 --> 00:51:51,178
The money would have to go
directly to you.

737
00:51:51,355 --> 00:51:53,380
That's gonna make Grandma really mad.

738
00:51:53,557 --> 00:51:55,991
Because my mother
will raise hell about it.

739
00:51:56,994 --> 00:51:59,588
-l mean, heck.
-You don't have to worry about her.

740
00:51:59,763 --> 00:52:02,891
Just worry about these kids.
You got a checking account?

741
00:52:03,066 --> 00:52:05,227
-l can get one.
-What about an apartment?

742
00:52:05,402 --> 00:52:07,370
l found one. lt has to be approved.

743
00:52:07,538 --> 00:52:10,530
How will you handle it?
You got telephone, electricity.

744
00:52:10,707 --> 00:52:13,301
These children gotta have
their own bed, dresser.

745
00:52:13,477 --> 00:52:16,139
-Yes, l have the list.
-This is ridiculous.

746
00:52:16,313 --> 00:52:19,805
-l'll give you a week to get it all in order.
-l can do it, judge.

747
00:52:19,983 --> 00:52:23,976
Well, if you can do all that, maybe
we should give you a job around here.

748
00:52:24,388 --> 00:52:27,289
Okay.

749
00:52:27,458 --> 00:52:31,394
This is just temporary,
but we're gonna give it a three-month trial.

750
00:52:31,562 --> 00:52:35,726
But l'm gonna be watching you. l want
reports from the doctor, the dentist...

751
00:52:35,899 --> 00:52:38,595
...and copies of report cards.

752
00:52:38,969 --> 00:52:44,305
This is highly unusual, but l'm giving you
a chance to keep your family together.

753
00:52:44,475 --> 00:52:46,568
l hope it doesn't come back
to haunt me.

754
00:52:46,743 --> 00:52:49,644
-Thank you, Judge Donner. Thank you.
-Next case.

755
00:53:04,161 --> 00:53:06,891
Tough neighborhood. l don't know.

756
00:53:07,064 --> 00:53:12,058
lt's better than most places we've lived,
and we can stay in the same schools.

757
00:53:13,136 --> 00:53:14,763
Well...

758
00:53:15,772 --> 00:53:18,206
...you're gonna have to clean it up.

759
00:53:19,042 --> 00:53:23,308
l have plenty of experience
scrubbing out bathtubs and cupboards.

760
00:53:23,747 --> 00:53:26,307
Well, put some pictures up.

761
00:53:26,483 --> 00:53:29,850
Family stuff. Make it cozy and warm.

762
00:53:30,020 --> 00:53:33,387
-l'll be back in a week.
-Does that mean you approve it?

763
00:53:35,025 --> 00:53:36,253
Done.

764
00:53:38,762 --> 00:53:42,562
-You did this without telling me?
-l was afraid you'd think l was nuts.

765
00:53:42,733 --> 00:53:44,530
No, my parents think you're nuts.

766
00:53:44,701 --> 00:53:47,329
l, on the other hand,
think you're incredible.

767
00:53:47,504 --> 00:53:51,167
l didn't have a choice.
Before l know it, l'm picking out beds.

768
00:53:51,341 --> 00:53:54,902
-What do you think of this one?
-lt's way too soft. You know what?

769
00:53:55,078 --> 00:53:57,603
We got a twin bed in the garage.

770
00:53:58,382 --> 00:54:00,748
Okay, how much money you got?

771
00:54:00,918 --> 00:54:03,978
l've saved a few thousand,
and with the foster-care money--

772
00:54:04,154 --> 00:54:07,021
Wait a minute. You've been saving
your money in a sock?

773
00:54:07,190 --> 00:54:09,283
Yeah, underneath the mattress.

774
00:54:09,459 --> 00:54:13,361
Why didn't you just put it in the bank,
you know? Earn some interest.

775
00:54:14,631 --> 00:54:15,620
What's that?

776
00:54:15,799 --> 00:54:19,394
The bank pays you a percentage
for the use of your money.

777
00:54:19,903 --> 00:54:21,996
Free money?

778
00:54:22,472 --> 00:54:27,432
That is a great, great idea.

779
00:54:47,164 --> 00:54:51,123
-This thing's awesome!
-Go, Gracie, go! Go, Gracie, go!

780
00:54:54,905 --> 00:54:56,497
Grandma...

781
00:54:57,808 --> 00:55:01,266
...could you cut this for me
right there on that line?

782
00:55:02,512 --> 00:55:05,879
Left, left, left, right, left.

783
00:55:06,049 --> 00:55:11,351
-Up the stairs.
-Left, left, left, right, left.

784
00:55:28,605 --> 00:55:33,099
We found a kitten!
Can we keep him, please?

785
00:55:33,276 --> 00:55:36,905
Yes, we can. You all are gonna
be taking care of him, okay?

786
00:55:37,080 --> 00:55:38,911
What do we call him?

787
00:55:39,082 --> 00:55:41,880
-Lobo.
-That's a good name.

788
00:56:06,209 --> 00:56:08,473
Okay, thank you, Jonny.
That's good enough.

789
00:56:08,645 --> 00:56:11,671
What did l tell you?
We do not jump on the furniture.

790
00:56:11,848 --> 00:56:15,511
Put it in the corner. Thank Mrs. Turner
when we give it back to her.

791
00:56:15,686 --> 00:56:19,782
We don't have any pictures,
so what pictures do we put in the frames?

792
00:56:21,191 --> 00:56:22,886
Keep the ones that are in there.

793
00:56:23,060 --> 00:56:26,461
lsn't Mr. Bessey supposed to be here?
l'm late for my open house.

794
00:56:26,630 --> 00:56:29,793
-Don't worry. He will be here.
-Now can we go out and play?

795
00:56:29,966 --> 00:56:32,696
No, l don't want you guys
getting all dirty again.

796
00:56:32,869 --> 00:56:35,895
Mr. Bessey is never late,
so something must have come up.

797
00:56:36,073 --> 00:56:39,634
Okay, that's him. Okay, come on.
Come on, come on, come on.

798
00:56:41,478 --> 00:56:43,742
Okay, everybody ready? Clean hands?

799
00:56:44,448 --> 00:56:46,006
Elbows?

800
00:56:46,183 --> 00:56:47,810
-Okay, good.
-This is such bull!

801
00:56:47,984 --> 00:56:51,715
-We're gonna miss the whole thing.
-Calm down, Ryan.

802
00:56:53,390 --> 00:56:56,325
Hello. l'm Sandy Jacobs.
l'm your social worker.

803
00:56:56,493 --> 00:56:59,929
Hi. You know what?
There might be a mistake.

804
00:57:00,097 --> 00:57:03,066
Bob Bessey, Mr. Bessey,
he's actually our social worker.

805
00:57:03,233 --> 00:57:06,134
Your file's on my desk now.
That's the way it works.

806
00:57:06,303 --> 00:57:07,770
Okay.

807
00:57:08,839 --> 00:57:10,397
You're late.

808
00:57:10,574 --> 00:57:12,201
-Sorry. Traffic.
-Yeah, right.

809
00:57:12,375 --> 00:57:14,275
We have a phone.
You could've called.

810
00:57:14,444 --> 00:57:17,811
They're upset because they had
an open house at school tonight.

811
00:57:17,981 --> 00:57:19,881
Yeah, it started an hour ago.

812
00:57:21,251 --> 00:57:25,415
Yes, well, this takes precedence
over an open house at school.

813
00:57:29,192 --> 00:57:31,456
lt's very homey.

814
00:57:31,628 --> 00:57:34,722
-You have gas, electricity?
-Look at our kitten, Lobo.

815
00:57:34,898 --> 00:57:37,458
lt means ''wolf'' because he bites.

816
00:57:39,169 --> 00:57:41,364
-We got our teeth cleaned.
-Me too.

817
00:57:41,538 --> 00:57:45,440
Yes, l have the reports.
Who are these people?

818
00:57:46,309 --> 00:57:48,834
Aunt Beth Ann and Uncle Mike.

819
00:57:49,613 --> 00:57:52,844
-And where do they live?
-Portland.

820
00:57:53,016 --> 00:57:54,745
They do?

821
00:57:58,989 --> 00:58:03,585
Okay, l noticed in the report that
your Grandma Lou checks here regularly.

822
00:58:03,760 --> 00:58:07,787
-We have a stable support line.
-Very stable.

823
00:58:08,231 --> 00:58:12,133
And l noticed that Brian
has communication problems.

824
00:58:12,302 --> 00:58:14,167
Do you mean Ryan?

825
00:58:14,337 --> 00:58:16,703
Oh, yes, Ryan. Sorry.

826
00:58:16,873 --> 00:58:19,034
So many families. So many children.

827
00:58:19,209 --> 00:58:22,576
l don't wanna upset him.
l would rather discuss this in private.

828
00:58:23,180 --> 00:58:25,614
l think you should consider
counseling for him.

829
00:58:27,651 --> 00:58:30,950
That-- That's a great idea. l will do that.

830
00:58:31,121 --> 00:58:34,113
Okay, well, l have to make my report
to the judge.

831
00:58:34,825 --> 00:58:37,453
All in all, l would say, ''Good job.''

832
00:58:37,794 --> 00:58:40,627
l'm gonna grant you
a three-month extension.

833
00:58:41,765 --> 00:58:43,665
Good work, boys.

834
00:58:50,674 --> 00:58:54,371
Grace, l have got to hand it to you.

835
00:58:54,544 --> 00:58:57,741
You have a lot of patience.

836
00:58:58,048 --> 00:59:02,075
And you're a better mother
than l ever was.

837
00:59:02,252 --> 00:59:05,483
Grandma, we never could have
done all this without you.

838
00:59:06,590 --> 00:59:08,490
Who drank all the milk?

839
00:59:08,658 --> 00:59:12,617
lf you drink all the milk, we don't have
anything left for the week.

840
00:59:13,196 --> 00:59:15,255
Why couldn't we get cereal?

841
00:59:15,432 --> 00:59:18,799
Because it's too expensive.
Ryan will eat the whole box.

842
00:59:18,969 --> 00:59:21,301
lt's got too much sugar.
You're hyper enough.

843
00:59:21,471 --> 00:59:25,066
-Gracie, who are those guys?
-Mind your own business. Get in the car.

844
00:59:30,981 --> 00:59:32,608
Down, Robbie! Get down!

845
00:59:34,217 --> 00:59:36,845
Gracie! Gracie!

846
00:59:37,721 --> 00:59:38,983
Stay down, Robbie!

847
00:59:41,391 --> 00:59:43,222
lt's okay.

848
00:59:44,561 --> 00:59:46,222
lt's okay.

849
00:59:49,966 --> 00:59:52,696
You can't give us any description
of the shooters?

850
00:59:52,869 --> 00:59:55,804
You didn't notice the make,
the color of either vehicle?

851
00:59:55,972 --> 00:59:58,941
l was covering up my brother.
That's all l thought about.

852
00:59:59,109 --> 01:00:01,509
-Where exactly were you?
-Where were you?

853
01:00:01,678 --> 01:00:04,272
Don't talk to my sister like that.
She pays taxes!

854
01:00:04,447 --> 01:00:07,473
-Show some respect.
-You were caught in a crossfire.

855
01:00:07,651 --> 01:00:11,644
They shot our car! Through the door,
the rear-view mirror, the windshield!

856
01:00:11,821 --> 01:00:15,450
-They blew a tire off! My sister came home--
-Ryan, get a grip!

857
01:00:18,094 --> 01:00:20,790
Go upstairs. l'll be up in a minute.

858
01:00:22,599 --> 01:00:24,533
Now!

859
01:00:26,369 --> 01:00:28,701
Excuse my brother.
He thinks he's my husband.

860
01:00:28,872 --> 01:00:31,739
This is all so terrible.
You could have been killed.

861
01:00:31,908 --> 01:00:33,842
Grandma!

862
01:00:34,477 --> 01:00:37,708
Robbie, honey, go upstairs
and get ready for bed. Take Lobo.

863
01:00:37,881 --> 01:00:40,111
Jonny will read one of the stories
we bought.

864
01:00:40,283 --> 01:00:42,376
Good night, Mr. Policeman.

865
01:00:42,552 --> 01:00:44,884
-You are not helping this.
-l know.

866
01:00:45,055 --> 01:00:47,922
l shouldn't have said that,
but l couldn't help myself.

867
01:00:48,091 --> 01:00:51,026
-l know, Grandma.
-These things were always happening...

868
01:00:51,194 --> 01:00:54,561
-...to your mom.
-Gracie! l came as soon as l could.

869
01:00:54,731 --> 01:00:56,494
You okay?

870
01:00:58,401 --> 01:01:00,460
-What's wrong?
-l think l'm gonna puke.

871
01:01:06,543 --> 01:01:08,773
Okay, you guys say your prayers?

872
01:01:08,945 --> 01:01:11,539
All right. Good night.
Don't let the bedbugs bite.

873
01:01:11,715 --> 01:01:14,513
-Good night.
-Good night, Tommy.

874
01:01:19,456 --> 01:01:20,445
Hey.

875
01:01:21,458 --> 01:01:22,516
Hi.

876
01:01:23,493 --> 01:01:26,485
l can't believe you threw up
on that cop.

877
01:01:26,997 --> 01:01:29,864
Yeah, it was a real projectile too.

878
01:01:30,367 --> 01:01:34,201
lt was a freak accident.
lt could have happened to anybody.

879
01:01:34,971 --> 01:01:40,136
lt just brings up so much old stuff,
you know, with my mommy.

880
01:01:42,779 --> 01:01:44,747
lt's like nothing has changed.

881
01:01:45,015 --> 01:01:47,711
You're not in that life anymore.

882
01:01:49,386 --> 01:01:52,321
-lt's time we made plans.
-Plans?

883
01:01:52,489 --> 01:01:55,390
Tommy, l can't even plan
on lunch next week.

884
01:01:55,558 --> 01:01:57,822
l'm going to court
every time l turn around.

885
01:01:57,994 --> 01:02:00,554
l'm going from social worker
to social worker.

886
01:02:00,730 --> 01:02:03,494
l have to do the laundry
and the groceries by myself.

887
01:02:03,666 --> 01:02:06,430
-l put shoes on their feet.
-They're getting older.

888
01:02:06,603 --> 01:02:09,128
Your grandmother can take over soon.

889
01:02:10,907 --> 01:02:15,708
-You're not hearing me.
-l'm hearing you, baby. Yes, l am.

890
01:02:16,112 --> 01:02:18,478
Next year, we're gonna get
our own place.

891
01:02:18,648 --> 01:02:20,878
l'm gonna go to Braxton.
You'll go with me.

892
01:02:21,051 --> 01:02:24,885
-Tommy, l can't afford college.
-On a scholarship.

893
01:02:25,055 --> 01:02:29,048
Gracie, you're getting A's and B's.

894
01:02:30,326 --> 01:02:32,453
Baby, l love you.

895
01:02:33,530 --> 01:02:37,193
We're gonna get through this together.

896
01:02:38,435 --> 01:02:40,630
Think about you for a change.

897
01:02:44,007 --> 01:02:45,474
Forget about it.

898
01:02:47,444 --> 01:02:49,105
Think about it.

899
01:02:53,616 --> 01:02:55,880
Right now l'm thinking
about something else.

900
01:03:08,465 --> 01:03:12,060
-So, what do you think now?
-lt's very ivory-tower.

901
01:03:12,235 --> 01:03:14,703
-You like?
-l like. For you.

902
01:03:14,871 --> 01:03:17,533
What makes you think
they'll give me a scholarship?

903
01:03:17,707 --> 01:03:20,437
-This. l went on the lnternet.
-By yourself?

904
01:03:20,610 --> 01:03:24,410
Oh, very funny. Look,
foster-family scholarship application.

905
01:03:24,581 --> 01:03:27,709
-All you have to do is apply. lt's a lock.
-Yeah, right.

906
01:03:27,884 --> 01:03:30,682
-Do you know what a college degree means?
-More money?

907
01:03:30,854 --> 01:03:32,378
No, more us.

908
01:03:32,555 --> 01:03:35,456
You know, have our own kids,
start a family.

909
01:03:35,758 --> 01:03:37,726
lnstant family, just add Tommy.

910
01:03:38,528 --> 01:03:40,223
You want?

911
01:03:43,366 --> 01:03:46,096
Yes. Tommy, l want very much.

912
01:03:46,669 --> 01:03:48,432
Good.

913
01:03:51,908 --> 01:03:54,206
l've never once seen you take a break.

914
01:03:54,377 --> 01:03:57,505
l'm applying for a scholarship,
so wish me luck.

915
01:03:57,680 --> 01:04:01,047
College? l thought you were saving
for a wedding dress.

916
01:04:01,217 --> 01:04:05,313
That'll come later.
And l'm renting a wedding dress.

917
01:04:05,488 --> 01:04:08,719
l'm not gonna buy anything
that l'm only gonna wear once.

918
01:04:09,692 --> 01:04:11,159
Hello?

919
01:04:11,327 --> 01:04:13,557
Gracie, it's for you.

920
01:04:24,440 --> 01:04:26,135
Grandma.

921
01:04:26,309 --> 01:04:28,971
Hi. l'm here.

922
01:04:29,145 --> 01:04:30,874
lt's gonna be okay.

923
01:04:31,047 --> 01:04:32,776
Rowena?

924
01:04:32,949 --> 01:04:35,611
No, no, Grandma. lt's Gracie.

925
01:04:35,785 --> 01:04:39,516
You're running around
without your shoes...

926
01:04:39,689 --> 01:04:42,214
...like when you ride your horse.

927
01:04:42,392 --> 01:04:46,658
-l told you a million times.
-No, Grandma. lt's Gracie.

928
01:04:46,829 --> 01:04:49,297
l've got my shoes on.

929
01:04:49,532 --> 01:04:52,194
l knew you'd come, Rowena...

930
01:04:52,368 --> 01:04:55,735
...because you know
how much l love you.

931
01:04:55,905 --> 01:04:57,770
You know l spoiled you.

932
01:04:57,941 --> 01:05:01,433
l spoiled you when you were a little girl,
but l was too strict...

933
01:05:01,611 --> 01:05:04,671
...in all the wrong ways.

934
01:05:06,516 --> 01:05:09,917
Parents aren't always so smart.

935
01:05:10,486 --> 01:05:14,650
But l promise,
l'm gonna make it up to you.

936
01:05:14,824 --> 01:05:20,353
Oh, forgive me, Rowena, please.

937
01:05:20,530 --> 01:05:22,555
You forgive your mama?

938
01:05:23,032 --> 01:05:27,731
Yeah. Yeah, l forgive you.

939
01:05:30,540 --> 01:05:33,202
Just rest now, okay?

940
01:05:34,010 --> 01:05:36,638
Just rest because l need you.

941
01:05:37,614 --> 01:05:39,946
We all need you.

942
01:05:41,784 --> 01:05:43,809
Just rest.

943
01:05:45,555 --> 01:05:48,422
Lord, when we hear the words
of your commandments...

944
01:05:48,591 --> 01:05:50,923
...that you giveth and you taketh away...

945
01:05:51,094 --> 01:05:55,622
...so often we look only at the part
that's half empty, the taketh away.

946
01:05:55,798 --> 01:06:00,132
Yet, even as we are filled with sadness
for the loss of our beloved Louella...

947
01:06:00,303 --> 01:06:03,329
...we are also here to celebrate
what she gave us.

948
01:06:03,506 --> 01:06:08,443
Louella Larson, proud mother to a fine
